<DOC><DOCNO> WSJ870506-0112 </DOCNO><HL> Gleason Corp. Sees RiseIn Earnings for the Year</HL><DD> 05/06/87</DD><SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO><IN> GLE </IN><DATELINE> ROCHESTER, N.Y.  </DATELINE><TEXT>   Gleason Corp. said it expects higher profit in 1987 but didn't make a specific forecast for the year.    In 1986, the maker of gear production equipment and automated manufacturing systems earned $347,000, or six cents a share, on sales of $252.2 million. &quot;In general, we expect the year to get better as it goes along, with significant improvement in the second half,&quot; James S. Gleason, chairman and president, said at the annual meeting.    Gleason posted a 1987 first-quarter loss of $894,000, which included a net charge of $952,000 from the sale of the company's Alliance Automation Systems division, on sales of $52.4 million. </TEXT></DOC>